----- Original Message -----
From: <manus@server.python.net>
To: <THurley@meyerglass.com>
Sent: Thursday, May 27, 1999 1:53 PM
Subject: Re: Hasbro Diplomacy Unleashed


>
> Okay, let's see here. These are in no particular order.
>
> First, some groundwork.
>
> Tell us a little bit about yourself. (Others you get in on this
"interview"
> should do the same, of course.)
>

I am an Assistant Producer on this project, interfacing with you and the
community at large is one of the many duties assigned to me. I am also 
one
of the Dip players previous to the project.

Here is some info on the rest of the team.

Mark Manyen is our Studio Head and has been in computer games since 
1986,
working on titles like the Chessmaster Series.

Jim Haldy is the Meyer/Glass Producer on Diplomacy, he ia a 12 year 
veteran
of the games business with over 50 titles shipped.

David Locke is our Senior Designer and has been involved in all aspects 
of
computer games for 10 years.

Kurt Mitchell is the Lead Artist on Diplomacy.



> Size of the development team involved in the Dip project?
>
8 people, full time, and a few others that helped out.

> How many were familiar with Diplomacy beforehand? (And how familiar?)
>
4 of the 8 above were familiar before starting, all of the designers and
producers.

> How long did the development take?
>
We started in April 1998, and we expect to ship in October 1999.

> What language was it written in (just for my own info, actually)?
>
C/C++ and very tiny bits of Intel assembly, mostly for graphics 
performance.

> Diplomacy is rather unique among games in its variability, and as you
know,
> a jillion different "variants" exist. Was any thought given to making 
the
> product adaptable for other maps? If so, how easy would it be for the
hobby
> to set up a map "plug-in" collection or to work with you and Hasbro to
> provide for the expandability of the game?
>
We are providing only the standard map (Eroupe 1901). We started out the
project thinking that we would do a bunch of maps, but, as we started on 
the
"Classic" map we found that the art time required was tremendous and 
stepped
back to a more do-able set of maps, which is 1 I am sorry to say. I 
would
assume that other maps may be sold as expansion packs if the original 
game
sells well enough to warrant them.

The art requirements, as expalined to me, are great and I am not sure 
that I
understand them myself.


> What would you say were the most difficult hurdles?
>
The hardest part of the project is the AI and rules engine. The rules
because of the "human" nature of them. I mean that the rules are written 
is
a way for humans to understand by a leap of intuition, coding them and 
all
the strange quirks was very difficult. The AI is by far the biggest
problem, I mean how do you go about emulating a human and human thought
process? Odi has been working on the AI since the beginning and will
continue until gold master.


> I see that you mentioned Ken Lowe's judge. Was the actual (spaghetti)
code
> ever referenced?

I think someone here read it and decided that we would not use it. We 
did
use it to verify that we were getting the same results from our "judge" 
and
as a model for the compromises to code the rules.

>
> Is the Ken Lowe rule that convoy paths must be explicitly spelled out 
used
> (frankly, I hope it is)? If not, how are the "unwanted convoy" and the
> convoy disruption rule handled?
>

Yes, you must specifiy each fleet in the convoy chain for the army being
convoyed. This is one of the places we looked to the internet judge code
for solutions.


> How is Pandin's Paradox handled?
>
I am not familiar with that... Please send examples and I will get back 
to
you.


> How much material on tactics is provided with the game? That is, is a
> "help" system in place that actually incorporates the "Library of
Diplomacy
> Openings" and "The Library of Diplomacy Tactics" (examples from The 
Pouch)
> into it?
>
We have our computer players selecting opening moves from a list of
"standard" opening moves in order to give the computer player a better 
Fall
1901 and Spring 1902 position to work from. Some of these moves came 
from
The Pouch, some from our own games. We have not yet implemented help or 
a
tutorial.

> Speaking of The Pouch, I am curious as to whether it was used (and if 
so,
> how heavily) as a source of information for you and your team.
>
We read it and we did use some of the information (see opening moves 
above).

> Are you aware of any upgrades that Hasbro has planned for you guys to
> do in the near or longer term?
>
Nope. We assume that the sales numbers will drive expansions.

> Are you aware that you have the best job in the world, having been 
paid to
> code a Diplomacy adjudicator? Are you guys hiring?
>
We do know that we have the best jobs in the world, not just due to the
Diplomacy Project but because we create games. Are we hiring? hmmm....
that's a loaded question. If I say yes, will I get flooded with resumes?
Actually we are not currently in a hiring mode, we are a small developer 
in
Chicago and need to sign a new contract in order to do any hiring. The
diplomacy team already has a new project, but, we are looking for 
another
title for our other team. We may be hiring soon...


> Please tell us a little bit about the AI. How are negotiations 
handled?
> How complicated can they get? Do you simply propose moves (or ask for
> certain moves NOT to be made) and get a yes/no answer [which could be 
a
> lie]? And receive similar proposals deom the AI players? Are DMZ's
> negotiated by the AI players? How about medium to long-term goals,
> such as a division of a specific set of SC's to be taken?
>

The game has a negotiation phase which is broken down into two areas; 
the assembly room where all players ( including AI ) start, and the 
meeting rooms where players go off to negotiate in private. Up to six 
players can be in a meeting room at one time. Within the meeting room 
human players can construct offers for other human players and also AI 
players. At the same time players will receive offers from other human 
players and AI players. These offers can include allying ( or not ), 
attacking, moves, convoys, DMZs, bounces, and hearsay. You and the other 
players, both human and AI, are free to except or decline these offers. 
But in no way are you or the AI players bound to their acceptance. The 
AI prioritizes its goals and compares that with offers made to control 
its movement. The best AI ( we will have three ) will plan and look more 
turns out.




> Is the system meant for real-time play only or are PBEM-esque games
> (lasting weeks and months) possible. That is, must all players who 
wish
> to communicate with each other be "online" with each other at all 
times
> during the game? If so, I assume that (a) games can be saved until all
> players are online again if a break is needed and (b) PBEM games are 
being
> left to the existing systems (i.e., the judges)??
>

We will have four play modes in Diplomacy; Single player against 
computer opponents, Multi-player over a LAN or the Internet, Hot Seat 
for multiple players on one computer, and a PBEM mode.


> Assuming a "real-time" mode is played, how are deadlines set and 
handled?
> How about deadline misses? Do powers get put into civil disorder? How
> are deadlines extended by players if more time is wanted/needed?
>

Diplomacy has the ability to set timers for each of the game phases. If 
a timer is set on and runs out of time, the game will try to advance to 
the next phase. For players who want no time limits, all of the timers 
can be turned off.


> Is there a turn rollback mechanism?
>

No.=20


> Is there any restriction on "press"? I have heard that there is a 
"chat"
> room concept into which you can invite any other player(s), but is 
there
> also the ability to send messages for reading later (a la PBEM)?
>

In a multi-player game, messages are sent to where you are; if you are 
in the assembly, than all other players in the assembly can see your 
message. Likewise, if you are in a meeting room, only those players in 
the meeting room will get the message. You must understand that we are 
recreating the board game and the look and feel is meant to be that of 
players sitting around playing face to face.


> Did you enjoy working on the project?
>
This question is unfair to ask at this time.

> Were any members of the development team involved in the organized
Diplomacy
> hobby before the project?
>
Nope, sorry...

> As a result of the project, have any members of the team become 
interested
> in the game when they were not before?
>
All of the team members have shown interest in playing to varying 
degrees,
again not really a fair question at this time.

> Have any members of the team become sick to death of Diplomacy? :-)
>
No Comment. ;)

> Those of us who use the Ken Lowe judge are very happy that you are
> making the new product compatible with input and output from the 
judges.
> Can you tell us more fully exactly what is being done?
>
Play by e-mail will be part of the product, but, we have not nailed down 
the
exact implementation


> I talked a bit about map variants. How expandible is the product so 
that
> it could handle more involved variants, such as my "Payola" and 
"Crystal
Ball"
> variants? (Obviously, I would love to see them implemented or
implementable
> if I have to do them myself :-)
>
No map or rule variants can be done at this time.

> The hobby considers itself to be the game's greatest asset and would 
like
> to be involved in making sure that Diplomacy is implemented and 
marketed
> in a way the game deserves. Do you know of any plans by you or Hasbro 
to
> involve representatives of the hobby in any advisory or quality 
control
> capacity?
>
I am not aware of any

> As you are aware, there are a great many Diplomacy tournaments and
> conventions scheduled every year around the world. Will your company
> or Hasbro be attending or promoting these types of hobby activities?
>

That is really a Hasbro question. They own the rights and are publishing 
the game. They have done some promoting of titles in the past, so I 
would hope that they will do so with Diplomacy.


> Do you have any knowledge of the NON-computer version of the game that
> Hasbro will release? (If so, similar follow-up questions, such as do 
you
know
> if Hasbro plans to include hobby promoting material in the boxed sets 
the
> way Avalon Hill used to do for the Postal hobby?)
>

Sorry, no idea.


> When do I sit to be videotaped and put on the "Tips from the Experts" 
part
of
> the CD? (Like Steve Mizerak in my "Virtual Pool 2" game :-)
>
> (Actually, this isn't a bad idea if you haven't already thought of it.
> Allan Calhamer, inventor of the game, would be nice to have 
immortalized
> on CD in your product -- I have his postal address if you need it. 
Other
> hobby legends (other than me, that it :-) like Edi Birsan should also
> be considered.)
>

This again would be a Hasbro thing.


> The Diplomacy hobby is truly international, as is made testament by 
the
annual
> world championships. Some of the best face-to-face players in the 
world
come
> from France and Sweden, and these players have become very good 
friends of
> mine and of other hobbyists here, via the World Championships and 
through
> e-mail. I have two questions here. First, is your product 
multi-lingual
> (I won't presume that it automatically runs outgoing player-to-player
messages
> through a http://babelfish.altavista.digital.com-like translator to 
render
> them into the chosen language of the recipient, though that would be 
very
> very cool and you might want to consider adding it, rather than 
forcing
the
> players to do the translation themselves), but rather I'm just asking 
if
the
> code itself has been internationalized? Secondly, European nations use
> alternate game-ending rules than do Americans. That is, Frenchmen play
> only the first eight game-years, and Swedes play only the first nine.
> This differs from the American way of playing until the game is won or
> drawn. Does your product support such alternate rules?
>

To the first question, yes. We will localize in 6 or 7 languages. Also, 
within the game, if you use the icons to negotiate with, it will display 
in the correct language of the other player. That means if each player 
used a version with a different language, they could play a game. 
Secondly, we are working on a game editor which will give some 
flexibility in the game. We hope to be able to set various victory 
conditions.


> Could your product be used in a tournament setting, and if so, how 
much
> help would it be? (That is, would a tournament-arranger be included or
> possible, that would "score" and "seed" rounds using any of the 
accepted
> Diplomacy scoring systems?)
>

It is not designed for this. It is meant to be a stand alone product for 
gamers.


> Are you sure you don't want to hire me, if not as a coder, then as the
> guy who thinks up all this great new stuff for you to do?
>

Then Dave Locke would have nothing to do ;).


> Well, that's all I can think of for the first batch of questions. I 
look
> forward to your responses and thank you VERY MUCH for taking the time
> to do this!!!
>
> Stab you soon,
> Manus
