judges)??<BR>&gt;</P>
<P>We will have four play modes in Diplomacy; Single player against 
computer=20
opponents, Multi-player over a LAN or the Internet, Hot Seat for 
multiple=20
players on one computer, and a PBEM mode.</P>
<P><BR>&gt; Assuming a &quot;real-time&quot; mode is played, how are 
deadlines=20
set and handled?<BR>&gt; How about deadline misses? Do powers get put 
into civil=20
disorder? How<BR>&gt; are deadlines extended by players if more time is=20
wanted/needed?<BR>&gt;</P>
<P>Diplomacy has the ability to set timers for each of the game phases. 
If a=20
timer is set on and runs out of time, the game will try to advance to 
the next=20
phase. For players who want no time limits, all of the timers can be 
turned=20
off.</P>
<P><BR>&gt; Is there a turn rollback mechanism?<BR>&gt;</P>
<P>No. </P>
<P><BR>&gt; Is there any restriction on &quot;press&quot;? I have heard 
that=20
there is a &quot;chat&quot;<BR>&gt; room concept into which you can 
invite any=20
other player(s), but is there<BR>&gt; also the ability to send messages 
for=20
reading later (a la PBEM)?<BR>&gt;</P>
<P>In a multi-player game, messages are sent to where you are; if you 
are in the=20
assembly, than all other players in the assembly can see your message. 
Likewise,=20
if you are in a meeting room, only those players in the meeting room 
will get=20
the message. You must understand that we are recreating the board game 
and the=20
look and feel is meant to be that of players sitting around playing face 
to=20
face.</P>
